At the end of the exchanges, the Prague Stock Exchange turned in negative
After the fall of Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily exchanges.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the exchanges, the Prague Stock Exchange resumed with its fall the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in shares on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the plan to stabilize the US financial sector, is also noticeable in our home.
Fall of actions in Asia
The Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, even though the clues succeeded in clearing some of the losses during the day.
The Hong Kong stock exchange's Hang Seng index lost four per cent during trade, but later it eliminated part of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 per cent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the Chinese stock movement on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 per cent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney stock exchange lost more than five per cent, but eventually the losses were reduced to 4.3 per cent.
According to his index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange was losing 3.6 percent.
"The hesitation over rescue action in the US will affect financial markets around the world," observed Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Board.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, that is, independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong have the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will be affected.
The bloodbath of American actions
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which it should have spent up to $700 billion (nearly 12 billion from Kč).
The legislators thus reject the call for support of President George Bush's project.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, American stocks experienced a bloodbath and the main stock indices experienced the greatest fall in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven per cent, having fallen on such a scale for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in a free fall.
Congress ceded: US government can inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush agreed on a broader form of financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
American legislators made a decisive turning point in the talks on the adoption of a rescue plan in the form of financial aid of $700 billion (approximately 12 trillion kroner) granted to the US financial system.
However, success is not certain.
In fact, before the final version of the law can be published and put to the vote, Congressmans must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Says Sunday to Reuters Barney Frank, Chairman of the House's Banking and Financial Regulatory Committee.
According to sources, the plan should a priori be put to the vote in the Senate by Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be adopted should be a major psychological first factor in reviving financial markets.
Given the complexity of the mechanisms through which market support can be effective, a "disillusion" will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the form that the package of measures for market stabilization should have," entrusted the Democrat Nancy Pelosi to the Bloomberg Agency.
According to her, the final vote could be taken on Sunday.
During the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislators met with the U.S. Minister of Finance Henry Paulson, in order to give the bottom of the government a final form.
It should buy back unsaleable real estate assets from financial companies, which cause financial enterprises considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and must also be effective on the market.
We still need to pursue this plan to restore markets, but I think we are there," said Paulson.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on the declining equity markets.
According to Senator Démocrate, Harry Reid did not escape, so the legislators made it possible for Congress to reach a final agreement as early as Sunday.
In this way, they want to calm down investors before they start trading in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where Congress' decision could affect Monday's trade.
However, for the time being, it is impossible to state with certainty when the two Houses of Congress of the United States will proceed to the vote, or whether the negotiations will not be blocked at the last moment by any particular problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
Nevertheless, there will still be many changes to the law.
The total amount intended to support the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the opportunity to block the remaining amount by following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, then, finally, $350 billion.
Bush welcomed progress in the negotiations
Although the president may put his veto on this decision, Congress has the opportunity to put the latter in a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finance for the purchase of bad real estate securities, the value of which fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said that Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartite effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limiting golden parachutes
The Chairman of the Senate Banking Committee Christopher Dodd, Chief Negotiator, said that legislators had agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of contributors against losses, the adjustment agreement, and the progress of the plan on the axis of time.
The new Act also provides for the limitation of gilded parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the program and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this issue and have made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also provides for assistance for real estate owners, who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new instalments in the case of mortgages that it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing debtors to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to the chief economist of Patria Finance David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its realization will be very difficult.
"And this is due to the fact that we do not know what the mechanism and the price of buying back problematic assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the division of losses between the financial sector and the government," said Marek, this week at the iHNed.cz server.
If the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, Marek says it's not that important.
"It is much more important for the congressmen to agree, as early as this week, to support this plan and to devote it as soon as possible.
This psychological meaning of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, is most important at the moment," Marek stressed.
An intense fight to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We'll advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
However, there is sufficient reason to obtain an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a expensive high-end gramophone to put on Maxim Turbulenc's new album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl records, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are vinyl records in your shelves packed with rock art, jazz or blues, you're probably dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same applies to music during travel, i.e. compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
Here too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would find it difficult to support headphones purchased for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown functions, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
Besides the primary functions, telephone calls and texting, it is capable of playing music and movies, recording them, it has a camera of varying quality and can, for example, be used for navigation.
And if we take Smartphones and communicators into account, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no frigidarian can grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are almost witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal nature of the motive is not without drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between two reloads.
And reading music is one of the most important goinfres of energy.
There are few mobiles who are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is much lower.
In this respect, the music players (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly better performing.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, moreover, you sometimes call from time to time, get yourself, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this is valid even for more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, who are capable, following reloading, of a continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least efficient.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer without a special software.
One can, of course, record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without any reduction, given the tiny dimensions of memory cards used in mobiles.
As far as readers are concerned, you do not need any software except iPod.
Just fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will themselves create a media library classified according to the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or according to the user's judgement.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like the Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a specific device, focus on the battery life, the capacity of memory, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it that for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3.
Virtually all mobiles are capable of doing so today.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is capable of playing.
All manage to play the MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have this format.
It is one of the most common formats and, apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play music in WMA format.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods), on the other hand, is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of online music.
Just visit the corresponding operator's (or other supplier's) web pages from the mobile phone and purchase the song or album.
This service alone should be a compelling reason for obtaining a musical motive.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and in most cases it is limited to radio tubes quickly made.
Nor are prices the lowest.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, the Internet, or even the wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their motive on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to pull the motive out of your pocket, while you forgot your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you still have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which virtually all mobiles have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than three thousand.
For a prize of three four thousand crowns, one can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of an ordinary earphone output.
The price of the best telephones and the best tools, also equipped with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy order.
Really anyone manages to ensure the order of the most basic readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest ones (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the control to that of a cassette set, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a mobile internet connected by chance, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an exchangeable memory card slot (M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models support in principle only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones get away with even 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose more specialized mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, so that the control ease is close to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles from the walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went the farthest in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours) higher, is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on many occasions on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of a SMS was higher for us than for the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the European Commission's recent steps in regulating roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators cheaper than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there is no longer room for another operator, choruses with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network is apparently no longer very lucky (and now it would find frequencies only difficult).
However, there is still one possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable fall in prices, to which conventional operators had to react as well.
Yet, even before the entry of such troublemakers as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to those heard today at home were heard in Great Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the Virtual Operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let us add that behind Mobilking there is the financial group Penta, which owns among other things the U:fon in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators being the possibility to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators become low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited range of services.
For example, in Britain, Tesco Mobile offers text messages that are at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, relying on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity shot.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work at home as well.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone's spokesman, is in doubt: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very pro-active.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesman for the financial group Penta.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were not in any case in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera Group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the business customer field, has not for quite a long time been hiding its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile ones.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl's spokesman.
The future may therefore be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we could perhaps host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific ones.
For the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us," said Vlastimil Srše
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile's spokesperson Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not yet recorded a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
She adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator should appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs his attention to the completion of requests for his own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, in our view, means the most input from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in line with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a fall in prices and thus a decrease in their profit.
What is the point, then, of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to agree on themselves as larrons at the fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of U:fon also bears witness to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on ČTÚ, when U:fon was created, was exerted by T-Mobile.
This is reflected in the information available to the public from the ČTÚ web pages.
Today, however, U:fon lends itself as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: "Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry of a fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power in the Czech Republic to intervene in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
However, the latter adopted its typical position in the face of this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, as the offer of potential interested parties has not a priori presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of ÚOHS in reply to our question.
Such a statement would not surprise representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a declaration is more than confusing.
All the more so since Kristián Chalupa adds: "Across the border, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephone services."
However, exerting pressure in the direction of an honest functioning of the market and a fall in prices is apparently not part of the interests of ÚOHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to chance and the hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not noted any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecom regulator," said Chaloupa.
One of the many points of discord is the interpretation of the dominant position on the market.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets drawn up by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts suggest a different view: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators visibly proceed in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Putting responsibility on the ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in communications, by means of which the ÚOHS washes hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Regrettably, the recently adopted Telecommunications Act has not been able to bring about a broadening of ČTÚ's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
This, the representatives of the ÚOHS must know very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one's looking, it can work.
However, the functioning of a kind of virtual pseudo operators, many in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but the latter are only partly public.
In most cases, multi-level marketing firms are involved.
Specific mobile telephone services are offered by, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator is a typical business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she obtains special price offers (and others).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you're talking about happens, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would be looking at and that could lead to a halt in the collaboration with the company in question," answered our question on this Martina Kemrová problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such an activity has not reached the heads of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, they can be thousands of customers.
An operator, however, does not object to such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to the true virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are obliged to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the same way as ordinary customers of mobile operators."
This is precisely what should seem strange to ČTÚ.
In addition, there is another question to the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions forbid it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable fall in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators tried, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level, however, that regulators in developed countries have been involved, not in the interests of mobile operators, but in the interests of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulatory bodies deal with this issue as a hot potato that is disposed of by passing it on to a close target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is in these cases more than beneficial.
But let's not throw the handle after the bump.
If the background information says true and a virtual operator will soon appear at our home, the Czech mobile market may be back in motion.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will hardly be able to remain impassable in the face of rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Citizenship Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov msj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a men's or women's solo song, a chorus performance and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the anthem's arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national singing as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio station), he chose to perform solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, had a good diction, so that the lyrics could be understood well, that they could sing simultaneously," he said.
Next year, the Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary.
In 1834, the song Kde domov mőj sounded for the first time on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetteiers), an original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously adapted it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse naturally became part of the national anthem.
It remained one of seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
