Pragian public transport (MHD) will introduce the chip into their ticketing system on Wednesday
On Wednesday 1st October 2008 will be inscribed in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Pragian Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers, instead of having a paper ticket, will get into the metro, trams and buses will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, the latter is accessible to about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a coupon for 30 days or 90 days (it will be valid from 1 January 2009) and both have it registered on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (the Transport Agency), located in the Muzeum, Městek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Latviany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
From yesterday there is also the possibility of buying coupons via the Internet on the Dopravní podnik web pages: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people benefited from the service during the morning.
Those who will start using the online store may definitely forget the counters in the metro stations, where they had to trample with impatience in long queues so far in order to obtain paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon via the Internet and will be registered on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these contact points, there is at the disposal of the passengers a counter with trained staff, who will help the interested parties with the purchase via internet and, in addition, will register the coupon they have bought on their card," said the spokesperson for the Martin Opatrný project.
Besides the libraries, it will also be possible to record the electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, remind the machines to compost the tickets and the passengers may have already noticed them at the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today the city has five, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný added.
Automate will check the coupon instead of the driver
The automatons that will work from tomorrow, are easy to use.
Simply insert the Opencard chip card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the vicinity of the city.
