The Sudetes were calling for a referendum in the USA
The Sudeten Germans asked in 1945 for Šumava to be integrated into the United States.
This is the result of a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the Southern Bohemian).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the president of the US with such a desire.
This stems from, among other things, a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov pray in the letter to the US President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation and want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of Šumava is dear."
Given that the rallying to Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, dishonest attitude, incomprehension, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take in his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the quarter of a million inhabitants," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of post-war history, appear somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Germans of the Sudeten of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to see that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some were waiting for the United States and Great Britain to obtain a certain type of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war he was, as a German from České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When, at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," said Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war felt, according to him, that, following the Beneš decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
Emotional Campaign to Attack Drivers
Action aimed at the most costly road safety in Czech history.
A way to characterize the emotional media campaign that intends to launch, on Wednesday, the Ministry of Transport.
Minister Aleš's office believes that it will discourage drivers from engaging in dangerous driving behaviour.
This campaign costing 150 million will appear on television, radio, cinema, the Internet, but also on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from driving fast and driving alcohol.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
Above all, she wants to reach out to young drivers, bikers and pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
This is also reflected in the "bloody" slogan of the entire campaign:
You don't think - you pay!
The sentence "You don't think" is printed in capital letters on the license plate.
Then, in a puddle of blood, there's the phrase "You'll pay."
Which must symbolize that one can pay life for a moment of inattention.
The spots will "haunt" the spectators until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in the Anglo-Saxon countries, where images with drastic images of the victims of accidents can be seen commonly.
It believes that this will lead to a reduction in the accident rate and the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
The strategy of sugar and whipping against drivers
"What works with drivers is the system of sugar and whipping.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by saving time, when they grill a red light.
The whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
The risks must be reminded of the drivers," says Martin Kořán, transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
This is how we need information campaigns in the press and, above all, negative advertisements, the psychologist believes.
In his view, signs that signal the danger to drivers are already less effective.
"When a static panel that warns against a danger is installed, it will probably quickly merge with the environment and drivers will no longer notice it," Kořán said.
