Nights of insomnia for the shareholders of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, insisted the Federal Minister of Finance only a few weeks ago.
How fortunate that the politician used the word 'relatively' and that he slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, obtains from a consortium of German banks a credit of one billion to protect itself from market turbulence.
One person in the confidence of the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are issued up to EUR 35 billion.
The Hypo Real Estate should now pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
In the background, Depfa's daughter-society bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible since the mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced from 95 per cent to 2.37 million euros, the own capital rate had also slightly decreased from 1.6 to 1.45 per cent.
Current and net profits from financial transactions fell from the same period in the previous year to zero, profits from the allocation of specified receivables and securities and the termination of provisions in credit transactions had fallen from over 70 per cent to 5 million euros.
And it was only thanks to the large profits from the repayment of downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the repayment of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern companies that the shortfall in earnings of about 16 percent turned out to be moderate.
After its privatisation in 1990, the former state financier had first misspeculated on industrial real estate loans, which had then been wired to Aareal Bank.
Because conventional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa then became more intensively involved in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint projects between private investors and the State (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the daughter company, the Hypo Real Estate must carry out depreciations which should have an essential material effect on the calculation of the group's gains and losses, which nevertheless remains unclear.
The fact is that the dividends have been reduced.
Already for 2007, they had been truncated two-thirds.
The Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor since the acquisition of Depfa.
It is stronger than other institutions dependent on refinancing on the interbank market as it does not have any customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of credit between banks has again become considerably more difficult, with banks accumulating their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs a short-term refinancing medium for a portion of Depfa's total credits - about EUR 50 billion - annually.
According to a statement from the Hypo Real Estate, the group's financing requirement is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of international financial markets largely out of working order.
Other sources say that refinancing would be ensured through the funds until the end of 2009.
HRE Chairman Georg Funke explained, however, that the Hypo Real Estate Group should no longer have to resort to financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Institution for Supervision of Financial Services (Bafin) assume that the Hypo Real Group's market capacity is now assured.
The bank's shareholders and creditors can only hope so.
However, given the dynamics and imponderability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Moreover, it is not unthinkable that funding should not be used to its full extent.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest press releases, still at the gates of insolvency on Sunday late in the evening, this temporary rescue at least will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The share price fell from 75 per cent to 3.30 euros.
The price of bonds, on the other hand, is particularly good.
While debts in the first place have barely moved, the prices of second-rate loans are declining.
The most affected are the investment funds of the former daughter company Württemberg Hypo and of course those which have a lifespan beyond 2009.
The bonds of the bank Hypo Real Estate previously seemed to be an alternative speculative investment, now their value must be considered dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the institute itself which brought the crisis into the establishment by the acquisition of the bank Depfa.
As long as the issuing institutions, governments and less affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, it can be assumed that arrears will be resorption over time.
Or it will happen what no one dares to hope at the moment - that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed noises of partial nationalization, the probability that approached safety has now become a mere hope founded.
This should set aside nights of insomnia above all for long-term creditors on whether to separate themselves from their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn a line from to represent a carry-over of losses for the next few years on the next tax on capital income from automatically deducted equity gains.
