Rats also have sensations
A rat or a cockroach flees from danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we check that he feels the same way when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and approach the questions of the feeling or in general the consciousness, we enter into terrains that are difficult to practicable because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral Cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
So at least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the Prefrontal Cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to anticipate and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from the other primates.
Another significant feature could lie in the linguistic nature of man: much of his existence being linked to language, it often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that the animal consciousness, whatever the way it is produced, would probably differ a lot from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, as a result of this particular hardware, to be analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses major problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
One could examine animal consciousness processes without considering their content, and that is exactly what happened in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Curiously, this approach also highlights the weight of the Prefrontal Cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what is the result then for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we designate as "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defence system located in the brain (or its sequels, such as the reactions of the body) grabs alive memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the cortex regions that characterize primates and especially man.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volubile nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than to ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from primitive activities are born in the regions of the cortex and cerebral trunk, just like Jaak Pankseep, which is more focused on the brain stem.
As this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could fully participate in transversal sensations of any kind.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe that is indisputable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in both men and rats is likely to be felt as fear in both cases: how can we check whether rats and men feel the same way when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach flees from danger, but if he feels fear?
In my view, similar behaviours are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Of course, the nerve comparison helps: rats and men have similar brain trunks, but cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem at the origin of the sensations?
And even if we could prove this for humans: how can we demonstrate this in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, perhaps even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
