"I photograph the master out of the stage to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no tight clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, liberated from all tensions to obtain the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these unknown moments of the general public, where we discover to intimate gestures and stolen looks artists who do not care to get on stage.
The German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of a few performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less well-known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy ... captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you must not make photos on stage.
They have their own personality and character.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera moments of personality of flamenco stars."
Bauer began a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists, or dancers with a plaque camera with the "Popular Mining Song" festival in 1997.
They are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, reminisce of classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captures the public with his art.
The search for the essentials and magic was the constant of this work which we present these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project has turned into a flamenco anthology, which will soon be published in a book about the portraits exhibited at the gallery.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph people's portraits, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a more or less long moment.
I think in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters you sometimes don't know or who just give you a few minutes to get them a picture.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at number 20 of the rue de la Mata (street parallel to the People's Garden of Hercules) which will be open until October 16.
