"Sing of Mayo", Garci's dared bet
Based on the stories of Benito Pérez Galdós, José Luis Garci recreates the famous battle of the Spanish against the French in "Sangre de mayo", which is the most ambitious film in his filmography with nearly 15 million euros in budget.
The filmmaker has tried "to stage the many characters and to illustrate the social analysis" that he has always admired in the work of the famous novelist, he explained today during the presentation of the film, with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría at the head of the long list of actors.
The film, lasting more than two and a half hours, "Sangre de mayo" will be released in the cinema next Friday, which will then become a television series for Telemadrid of more than four hours.
A great admirer of Galdós's literature, José Luis Garci assures him of having made with this film "a child's dream" thanks to Esperanza Aguirre, who commissioned him, three years ago, to shoot a commemorative film for the two hundred years of May 2nd Madrid, something that he always accepted when the story was based on national historical facts.
The €15 million provided by the Commune of Madrid is a "one-off opportunity" for Garci to reproduce with the appropriate decorations and clothing the atmosphere of "a Spain that was the wrong leader for the fight, since the struggle for independence led the people to rebellions during the reign of Ferdinand VII", he said.
But the filmmaker regrets that he did not receive funding as for the films "Captain Alariste" or "The Ghosts of Goya" - more than double the one obtained for "Sangre de mayo" - because he could not shoot a few scenes written in a script signed by Horacio Valcárcel, with whom he collaborated for almost all of his career.
The filmmaker of "Volver a empezar" influenced on his usual way of working, on the staging of the actors, with whom he is accustomed to repeat before starting the filming and to whom he does not cast, since it seems to him "humiliating" and considers that "the role of the filmmaker is to go to the theatre and the cinema to keep informed".
Many actors in "Sangre de mayo" repeat in front of the camera, such as Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
Four times a candidate for the Oscar (he won one), Garci considers that the three candidate films that represent Spain this year at the Hollywood Academy, "Sangre de mayo", "Seven tables de billiards français" and finally the winner, "The Blind Sunflowers", are not representative of the young Spanish cinema, "which would deserve to be better known", he declared.
