She was a free dance dancer and an oriental dancer.
She had an exciting life, pioneering the liberation of the woman, such as Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was Buddhist and vegetarian and pleaded for the abolition of the corset that prevented the free movement of women.
The life of this woman who marked the history of dance in Europe of the inter-war period, fascinated Isabelle Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she offered me to perform the sevillane dancer Tórtola Valencia and it seemed incredible to me."
According to the dancer, "we are not trying to tell her life but to translate her thinking.
The titles of his dances made me think of flamenco.
Thus, "the butterfly dance" made me think of a popular Cuban dance and "the snake dance" to some tangos.
Her dance was sensual and they told me that my way of dancing was the same as hers," she says.
The staging was made thanks to two remarkable contributions: that of Miguel Poveda who will sing Isabela again in one of his shows, as he had done at "La puerta abietta"; and that of Professor Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to collaborate with the one who was his pupil.
"Matilde transforms Tórtola into a mature character.
I am happy because she has agreed to play a part in my work and it honors me. "
The staging was also done thanks to the musical composition and guitars of Jesús Torres y Paco Arriaga, the popular song by Michel Ortega, el Pulga y Moi de Morón, the percussions of El Pájaro, as well as the rape of Rafa El Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfra Juárez, "who plays the role of the eternal companion of this kind of artists who were considered divas".
This work also recounts, in a way, the life of this woman who exhibited herself in places so far away, especially for the time, as in India, the United States, or Russia, but also throughout Europe, since she usually lived in London.
"I wanted to remind her because I think it's these women who have a huge influence in their time and now no one knows and showcases her work," Bayón says.
