Recidivists from alcohol to the wheel will have to install the 'alcolock' system.
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative penalties for alcoholism, to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the vehicle from starting in a state of drunkenness, or if it does not blow.
The initiative was already announced last June and is now reflected in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project which will last a year.
Its aim is the rehabilitation of the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State responsible for road safety, as well as the Directorate General of Road Safety and the Foundation Technological Institute for Motor Vehicle Safety will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once in a state of drunkenness, take the car back.
Alcolock would avoid this because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol level in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not blow before; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than that allowed.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is borne by the driver.
In this respect, a study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced infringements by up to 65% in the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save the lives of 115 people every year.
This measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means, but criminal reform requires reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote for an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party that proposes to install this system in school buses as was done in France.
