Interview - Blood Back Safer
Hema-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
Above all, he regained the confidence of the public, who had been seriously shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the National Blood Reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public grunt, in February 1994, the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a disaster should not happen again.
While Justice Krever was slow to table his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Services to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started operations, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and field work in the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said, proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile".
From its inception on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, Europe was witnessing the outbreak of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, tells the story of the fort that has held since its foundation in 1998.
"And we did not know at all whether this disease could be transmitted by blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when it is not known and a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
As a result, in April 1999, people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 were refused blood.
A few years ago, it was shown beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode has shown us that the precautionary principle that has been applied makes sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which allow the presence of the virus itself and not of antibodies against the virus to be directly detected in the blood of donors, on which the tests used so far were based.
The NATs have helped to shorten the silent period, which extends between the moment the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors will be infected without knowledge and that they will not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I believe that you can now feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover your health," said the Chief Executive Officer of Héma-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
As soon as last year appeared on the island of Reunion the Chikungunya virus which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant," says Dr. Décary before pointing out that, in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
"The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or platelets to recharge.
The aging of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which has an average of only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
However, any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older who meets the eligibility criteria can give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a malaria-affected country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they age and can no longer give blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to restrain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Since today's life is so frantic, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec not only supplies blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is full of stem cell-rich blood that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to collect more than a thousand a year.
We should start proposing for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed to be unable to access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
