Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of Canadian Barrick Gold Mining.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has brought a six million defamation suit against three authors and a small, penniless publishing house with the aim of launching a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to lead to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and editor of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable money to prepare their defences and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of mining.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is, moreover, often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to frightening anyone who dares to look at the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of the public that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is being done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada normally take place through the exchange of ideas and not by batons.
It was therefore enough for mining to open its books, its files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects the petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada from the back of the hand.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he could both ask for a "public" debate and disregard the views of the same public.
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to heavily paid lawyers, not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports Black Canada's authors and publishers do so primarily because it rejects the brutal manner of mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a gag pursuit (pursuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a formal notice against the authors of Black Canada intimating them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's pursuit is a direct attack on academic freedom of research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to quote credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as well as for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit such abusive prosecutions.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and Congress leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for failure to pay, and a right of control over the salaries paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
The U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and the ordinary Americans from the ongoing Wall Street crisis," the Democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruptions on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had sprinted in the last few hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would cause on investors' mood.
The deadline that had been agreed was the opening of markets this morning.
The two candidates in the US presidential election, who were late in the negotiations, were rather in favour of the agreement, but they were not afraid of being forced to reach that end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama agreed with the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, such as the one to allow homeowners to keep their homes and the one on the salaries of executives of state-survived companies.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no reason to welcome them.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
Asked another channel about whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad lines I have read show that this is something that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of not doing anything is simply not acceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan is designed to buy back with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risky and unsold debts of U.S. financial institutions.
After 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of mortgage loans at risk (subprime) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a liquidity freeze and the debandad of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican elected officials who had overturned the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed that this impasse has emerged since the Democrats agreed that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty should only be insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round out the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to assume losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its bet.
The new plan provides for a first instalment of $250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion may be added if deemed necessary by the President.
The payment of another $350 billion is expected to be endorsed by another vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in the rescued companies that will pay him dividends in the event of profit and that he will be able to resell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure procedures for housing related to the real property loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on compensation and severance payments to the management of the affected companies.
The plan's architects would like to see it put to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Votes continued yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic sides.
"Evidently, Washington does not hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee, at the address of his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one of profiting from taxpayers."
Speaker of a small group in Congress known as the "sceptic caucus", Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economics professors, including three Nobel Prize laureates, wrote to us to tell us: Congress is being asked not to rush and to look carefully at the way ahead," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, we once again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was refusing to acquire its competitor in the midst of a shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of risk mortgages in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In exchange, we get a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It's just something that savers and households now appreciate that times are forecast to be uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government seemed to be nationalizing another bank that had been undermined by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all of the loans under way at Bradford and Bringley Bank, including more than 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) in real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to be nationalized by the British government since the beginning of this financial crisis.
