What could Zuschlag &amp; Company manufacture well in their invoicing factory?
In the near future, on 8 October, the hearings relating to the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are charged with fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, which has caused particularly serious damage, and other charges have been brought against them, such as false charges and the use of false charges.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the money from grants was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money of the state and the municipalities, about 65 million HUF in total, went on the one hand in the caisses of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other hand, in the pocket of some people.
Their method, which was also made public by the investigating authorities, was to collect the money from the grants obtained by issuing invoices for costs, behind which no actual services were provided and thus the associations never complied with their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while they made the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that would appear on the invoices, it was decided, inter alia, during the tours to the northern province of Lake Balaton, conducted by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's statement, he was to locate boarding houses and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices which they would introduce, among other things, from the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as from the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András 的ri, who, according to our information, was mainly responsible for drafting the files necessary for obtaining the grants.
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place provided the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up on behalf of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which will later bear the name of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, was full of errors of form and substance.
A boarding house, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three bedrooms, and up to ten people could spend the night there. However, the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty guests.
The issuers of over-imagined invoices also fell into excess when they mentioned Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounts, neither Jobb Jövőért nor Hoppá's name appeared, according to the information given to the prosecution.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told the website hvg.hu that when the prosecution summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew immediately that they were fake documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in a wrong place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that, according to the bill, a hundred people lived there, did not stick either, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have so much room.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
The issuers of zealous invoices also did not inquire about Budapest's travel agencies, which were part of their choice, but only organized trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also runs counter to the Agency's accounting practices.
Moreover, as it appeared during the survey, they also added VAT on these documents, while the services relating to travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices drawn up in the name of Hotel Revfülöp to the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's services did not bear a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. Moreover, the hotel's employees only issue printed invoices, while the false ones were written by hand.
The investigation by the Public Prosecutor's Office reveals that the "issuers" also made mistakes by mentioning as a service the transport of goods by road, which the company issuing invoices could not exercise, since its profile was the investment advice.
Moreover, it is also for defects of form, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont proved to be false.
Just as in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehertó's sports internship, both of which deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
The counterfeiters also paid no attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., based in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at home. According to our information, it is for this reason that the liquidator of the company denies having issued this invoice.
Invoices drawn up deliberately
Another category of invoice issuers is that composed of those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The foundation Esély Budapestért Alapítvány, at the request of the group of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, has drawn up an invoice to the order of the foundation Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, for a sum of HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was forced to issue false invoices by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, it cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently under liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the association Atlasz Egyesület and the association Vörösfenyő Egyesület, for an amount of approximately HUF 5 million, but after which no benefits were actually provided.
There was no financial movement either, since the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but the organizations avoided mentioning them in their accounts.
The following category of companies issuing invoices is that of companies directly linked to the accused.
For example, the administrative delegate of the managing director of Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the business of fuel and motor vehicles, whose head office was in Budapest, but where it was not found, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of IT equipment amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, the equipment was purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of the company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov also sent documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he issued invoices to the order of Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he seized their value.
It is precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of these companies were operating, which the accused explained because they were not getting work.
He still used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-accused and editor of the founding documents of the companies, he drew up invoices in their names, at the order of associations relating to Zuschlag, such as the Atlasz and Y-Generáció associations.
Kubatov has given organizations a total of 15 invoices issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade for a value of HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecution thought that 10% of the sums shown on the invoices as well as VAT went into Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up fictitious invoices that were used in the context of Biztos Pont's grant application.
In January 2006, the Association Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted a grant application to the public utility agency of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They received this grant for an amount of twice HUF 500,000, but these amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the application.
To prevent this from becoming known, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were submitted to TMA.
Moreover, these invoices were found during the search in the office of Árpád Kemecsei at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the accused will report on the method of making the invoices, as she had already done before before before the prosecution.
What could be really interesting would be that the main defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil over the whole story.
So far, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell the least details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or if so, the Socialists would have reached an agreement that in return for the repayment of a large part of the HUF 50 million, Zusi would be the sole one.
Today, the latter is probably upset, as applications for his house arrest, based on a reduction in his conditions of detention, continually fall into the ears of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and the perpetrators of unrepairable economic crimes, walk freely or at least, wait at their own home for the end of the proceedings. He does not have this possibility.
The psychology of the overbidding: why are we spending more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Neurology and economics researchers at the University of New York have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distracted in this type of competition, such as an eBay auction, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research has attempted to draw up a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a play auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which was the overbidding of a third, the whole under the brain stem, called striatum, moved intensively during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "self-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
That is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers have pursued financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups were outbid by a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the group about the real value of the product in question, and thus made their payment.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they would win the game, then they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
While the third group received the $15 before the auction, the group members also lost the money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was on victory in one group, while in the other, on failure.
By proving the neurologists' hypothesis, the players' team members "against failure" were willing to bets higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any already existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by leading, now, to a third explanation." - found Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that one hundred miles of the hepatitis virus-carrying patients in Hungary, but only seven miles are being treated. This is due to the fact that often patients do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to liver infections caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, are spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g., contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended that they be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no C vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated foods, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach aches and nausea.
Then a visible yellowness develops on the skin and on the white of the eye, the stools become lighter and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year around the world, one million people die of the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten patients is receiving medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know about the virus, because the pathogen causes a sneezing destruction of the liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms do not appear until after 20 to 30 years.
As a result, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users, and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your treating physician immediately upon observation of symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does the one who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would have already helped to make the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers at Oxford University have made an interesting experience by analysing the degree to which belief in God could influence tolerance to human pain.
As part of this strange experience, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments, in which academicians, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experiment takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and disseminating electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look in a sustained way at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with Hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experiment hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would evoke a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, was about its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time received 20 electroshocks in four parts succeeding each other, while looking at either the religious theme painting or the more general theme painting.
The Catholics declared that, in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt like "safe", like someone who was "cared for" and they "calmed, and peace invaded them".
In view of the painting of religious theme, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in the atheists, provided that the appropriate photo is found.
"We should find an image against which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, praised the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, actually changes our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, there is only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of subjects if we showed believers a Madonna painted by Leonard or by a painter of the same calibre?
Would the sight of a better Virgin Mary lead to better results?
