Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main ambition is to gather even more information about its users. This is necessary for Google's founders to be able to meet their original objective, which was to: "Let's collect in a system all the information in the world!".
According to the Google leader interviewed, after ten years of global sham work, they are still only at the beginning of their goals to be able to process all the information.
To the question: what will be there in five years? Schmidt replied that he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What can I do tomorrow?" or "What is the job that would best fit me?". However, software will only be able to answer this kind of question, simple at first glance, on the day when they know enough about the users.
It is not perfectly clear to all Internet users that the words used during Internet searches, the IP address of the computer launching the search, and the pages then viewed by interested persons are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can consult what they've been looking for, what they've clicked on. Thanks to this, in the long term, Recommendations, a program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and will submit products and services to us on the basis of our previous declarations and registered preferences.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if he looks at what my job is? Ask users, who are worried about Google's information monopoly.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can generate fear, and it is not remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom, or possibly revolt against power that can provoke counter-reaction among Internet users.
However, it is a confirmed fact that the terms sought are not only registered, but in justified cases, they are transmitted to a third party, and in such legal cases, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most resounding example of recent times is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian paedophiles, during which Google transmitted to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public page called Orkut, thus allowing identification.
Human rights-conscious Internet users were able to sigh a sigh of relief last May, when Google, with the electronic legal protection agency EFF, proved its right to court in front of the FBI. According to the ruling, in the future, Google will still not be obliged by any of the constitutional issues to disclose information about the FBI's secret request, of any kind.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms that it had won in relation to the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier. But ultimately, it fails to obtain the search lists of private users, nor the entire list of websites and keywords of the last two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is falsified by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their private sphere and their private domain suffer when they start using Google services. Therefore, they attack them in the spirit of revolt that is manifested against multinational companies proud of their conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and its "wildlife" bringing together enthusiasts, activists and enthusiastic computer users who appear in many countries see Google as the next generation of big companies, the "wired body," as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, who is catalogued as an invader of the world because of Windows, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for ID code, does not ask for money for its applications. The documentary code and the program package, continually refreshed, has a much more accessible, younger and cooler effect, faced with the practice of the official software giant.
The reason may also be that geeks see very accurately the problematic relationship between human rights and the Internet, and what the web 2.0, the most widely proclaimed key word of recent years, draws right behind it.
Indeed, web 2.0 does not concern anything other than collaboration, than the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind us, and that we use the channels of communication at our disposal, and while the dimension of these changes one by one, the essential thing remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can keep a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link them to other performances, such as Twinter, or last.fm, which are related to his musical habits. Then, he can link them to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also hold blogs, in which automatically appear their most recent photo galleries that they store on Flickr or Picasa.
While we can see many examples, such as the one of the girlfriend who easily understands in view of the morning photos taken by the circle of common friends, with whom her unfaithful friend spent the evening, or the one of the company that fired one of her employees, just for the sincere opinions that he wrote on his blog about top management, one can be sure of one thing: the term privacy is totally to reconsider nowadays.
The one who lives an online life is made up of what he shows of himself, and that is how one can define the principle hiding behind the behaviour of today's young people.
He wants to hide something, or at least, wants to try to bypass Google's monopoly, can do it (starting, for example, with Scroogle, using the Google search system, but, at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who deliberately do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them is not least. Google's online services, including word processing, image processing, reading information, can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not attached to huge servers and which do not assemble our best profile, having existed to date.
Public opinion awaits, without really hiding, the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
The company, with its present value of $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion). AdWords/AdSense advertising areas threaten advertising agencies' revenues, while services introduced at an ever-increasing rate are causing serious migraines not only to Microsoft, but to many other computer program creators.
However, critical observers find, besides all this, contradictions with worrying effects: for example, the company's top management refused, in its entirety, the employees' protests, after it doubled the price of business kindergarten and after the company considered the daily multiple restoration to be too expensive, taken at any time. All this seems derisory in addition to the fact that already in 2006, Google acquiesced before the Chinese government and according to the terms of their agreement, the company detects all the results that hurt the good taste, as well as the interests of the Chinese regime.
According to one of the company's internal rules, the new services are not announced only when they can be used. What is certain is that in the coming months and years, they will move the world on new points. While some think that Google's book and magazine scanning and archiving project takes on such important dimensions that society will soon find itself facing the US Supreme Court, others tremble in front of its Health system, because in this one, we can build a complete medical benefit from our results of previous analyses, our doctors and our problems.
