Smart car mimics bumblebee theft
What method would be better for developing technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, other than the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
Like, for example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at the CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave the strategic idea of starting the engineers at Nissan, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-robot control system, of type BR23C, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate aim being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own oval-shaped space, which in reality looks very much like our secure protective hull - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and public technological relations of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a crucial role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
He identifies the obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, he evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which turns him into an avoidance manoeuvre right away.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid the collision.
Unlike any existing system at present, this avoidance manoeuvre takes place entirely instinctively.
"If this were not the case, the mini robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the time being collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that the bees have to avoid the other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotary movement, the acceleration and the slow down as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini robot
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a larger energy concentrate, making their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should process and react to only a few incoming signals per second.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need memory of a gigabyte capacity, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology for instant avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will enter mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
