The written version of the plan was made public before the opening of Asian markets, Sunday evening at 8 p.m., Washington local time (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m., depending on Central European local time), but did not cause a spectacular rise in stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill in the name of the 2008 emergency economic stabilization law. Then, its fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday night, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, and then the White House also welcomed the news of the agreement.
"We are pleased with the progress made last night, and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," said Tony Fratto, White House spokesman.
In addition, the programme diverges from the initial proposal made by the Bush administration, which stated that the $700 billion had to be spent on a one-time basis for the purchase of securities for doubtful credits.
From now on, up to half of the $700 billion can be spent. The first $250 billion will be delivered immediately after Congress passes the law, probably on Monday. This first amount will be used by the Secretary of the Treasury to buy bad debts from banks, while the use of the extra $100 billion will be left to the President's discretion.
The program will be overseen by an independent body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also take part.
The expenditure of the second half of the $700 billion depends on a new Congressional decree.
Under the Act, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to implement a combined strategy: at the same time, it will be able to purchase doubtful debts, securities relating to mortgages and doubtful mortgages, as well as other types of "toxic" claims.
The appropriate departmental officials stated that the buybacks may take place as part of an auction, but also directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the opportunity to take part in an insurance programme, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools at the origin of the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damage.
Henry Paulson stated that the law provides the necessary tools to spend $700 billion for the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it is the vast buyback of doubtful debts, their insurance, or to avoid the risk of the system leading to the collapse of one or the other major financial institution.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready for the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the other hand, bank leaders in poor positions and waiting for state aid can expect their severance benefits, simply referred to as the Atlantic golden parachute, to be capped by the government.
Wage capping is mentioned only in specific cases, and limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat provides support to the company.
The principle of capping means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys back in an auction, they will levy an excess tax on the gilded parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Directly following the redemption of doubtful debts, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the leaders is not overstated.
In order for the image to be complete, it is necessary to add that the existing gilded parachutes are not changed. The ceiling applies only to new contracts, thus motivating participation in the plan.
This is the first time in the history of the United States that legal limits will be in force regarding the support of the Directors General - commented the chairman of the commission in charge of financial benefits of the Chamber of Deputies, Democratic Barney Frank.
In addition, the State acquires a right to acquire shares in the banks involved in the plan. In this way, the risk of taxpayers decreases, since they can even win in the business as soon as the economy and with it the banks saved fall on their feet.
The bill mentions that in the next five years, the President must submit a proposal to Congress that will decide how the losses will be returned to taxpayers from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed doubts about this plan.
That's not why the U.S. citizens have mandated us, it doesn't protect taxpayers' dollars - said California Republican MP Darrell Issa.
