Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices rose 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008, while they decreased by 3.9 percent compared to a year earlier.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices rose only to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic selling prices for the processing industry sectors rose by only 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, and second, the production of footwear with a 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher price levels of plastics and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the petroleum processing sectors (1.4 per cent), manufacturing of electrical machinery and apparatus (0.9 per cent), and a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
Prices for paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other processing industry sectors recorded an increase of between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which account for a significant share of domestic industrial production, prices rose by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales of the processing sectors, oil processing prices showed the most significant increase (32.4%).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices rose by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices rose by 11 per cent.
Price reductions occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other processing industries, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the whole processing industry, prices have risen by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 per cent higher than in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to the allocation of sectors, in August it was the sectors initiators of profit-on-investment that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7%).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices rose by 0.3 per cent, while prices in the energy and materials-producing sectors for further processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, there was the largest increase in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was estimated at 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-producing sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent.
Export prices for the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro, and 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
