Járóka said: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, in Paris, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, hosted by France, began as a representative of the current presidency of the European Union.
In his message before the plenary assembly, as one of the main spokespersons for the expert consultation, Lívia Járóka, MEP Fidesz European People's Party, drew attention to the segregations in education, because it is a violation of the law that most affects Roma children and thus one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister of Labour and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among the people invited to take part in the consultation are the European social partners, as well as the most prominent representatives of legal protection and European civil bodies, in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of the group of MP Fidesz Popular Party, Járóka warned that alongside the distinctions found during the hirings, the Roma disappear from the labour market, in the first place, as a result of their low qualification.
"An overwhelming majority of Roma young people do not have secondary diplomas, and as a result of poor quality elementary education, only a tiny part of them have the opportunity to obtain a higher education diploma."
Járóka also stressed that education as a basic human right plays a key role in the promotion of other fundamental rights.
Investment in the early education of Roma children means strengthening the economies of the member countries of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these relations in as wide a circle as possible, also between Roma and non-Roms.
The earlier a Roma child starts school, the more likely he/she increases his/her chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; by taxes paid from his/her income and consumption, he/she participates in the State budget.
"By virtue of their European Union nationality, Roma must be guaranteed their right to quality education, and be protected from low quality and sectarian education." - stressed Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, an objective-oriented and action-oriented European Union collaboration is needed for an immediate acceleration of the school desegregation process. To this end, compliance with existing and in preparation anti-discrimination directives is of paramount importance.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and the unemployed must be broken and the opportunities provided by democracy must be given to Roma children, so that they can participate as citizens of their own right in the future of Europe" - Járóka demanded.
On behalf of the European Year for Equal Opportunities for All, the objective of the Summit for Equal Opportunities in Europe, which has been held every year since the Berlin Summit last year, is to provide a single platform to support measures taken to promote equal opportunities and combat discrimination, both at European and Member State level.
