Mp3 reader pointed at, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to full-volume music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a press release in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unexpected and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"from this scientific report- let us read in the note- it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per day and week, risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I'm worried that such a large number of young people who frequently use mobile music devices and full-volume mobile phones can unknowingly damage their hearing irreparably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the scientific data- continues the person in charge- this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also re-examine existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"Scientists-concluded the Ue Executive- confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now discuss with the Member States and other interested parties what possible measures could be adopted to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to effectively limit these data using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to full volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the limits currently in force for the maximum noise level at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods of time risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
