The elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion rescue plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms it to us that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its moderate soul East Coast, favourable to federal institutions as well as to business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "the Washington ones" and to the world of finance, powerful especially in the central and southern states.
The soul, precisely, which made itself felt despotically with the vote I was talking about at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is just one example of the changes, the great changes that the current economic earthquake is pre-announced or is already letting go: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not just here.
In both the United States and Europe, the crisis seems to speed up the incubated phenomena for some time, so much so that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the revival, the extraordinary revival, of the two-tier sovereign state, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with foreigners, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families who live in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for whom it governs: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation seems really out of the question or has little to say: the obvious proof is given to us by the European Union, which, shared as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, is unable to decide on any common political line.
And so, it is the government of each state that all expect interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all an affection of credits: when we go through a difficult period, there is only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and legitimization to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements which no market or international organization will ever be able to dispose of in a similar way.
This new phase of the state-nation crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-greater importance that the more recent economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized that our future will have to settle its accounts more and more with the rather unmaterial things like water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth, but that are absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So, who is sovereign, certainly has more maps than the one who is not, that is, the one who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, provides for a fracture.
Which says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadows.
And in addition, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: a discredit, suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of distance that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of Western countries.
Thus further increases the conviction of the various classes, before actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of the majorities.
In short, The demand for leadership, feeds underground, a powerful and ramified movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised "revolts" of elections or, in the collective moods of recent times, from the conservative ascent in Austria Bavaria, the fall of Labour in Britain, the rebellion of American congressmen against Bush (and it may well be that the victory of the right in Italy has not happened by chance).
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, someone would say, have ever more difficulty, which does not date today, in understanding and thus representing the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis is strengthening, increasing and potentially agitating.
In view of all this, speaking of a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda seems frankly exaggerated.
But it is said, keeping eyes wide open, that is not without reason.
The superstick to walk on the walls.
Overcoming the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walking on walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centres, and today a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring only 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers managed to hold a 100-kilogram body on a vertical wall.
THE STUDY- The American journal Science published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular carbon structure, called nano carbon tubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged as a pile of spaghetti." Explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have drawn inspiration from the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that ensure the animal a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time that it "detachs easily from the wall" explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at Dayton University.
WALK ON MURS? –"This material could be used as a temporary adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe yes, but researchers are thinking of a much less fascinating use such as connection between electronic devices, since carbon nano tubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications may involve aerospace engineering.
For now, no superhero.
THE OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also dedicated to looking for a new adhesive.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, Californian researchers presented an adhesive made of microfibres like hair, which self-cleansing dust during movement on an area to ensure a perfect and constant adhesion.
