The Nobel Prize in Economics to Paul Krugman.
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to American Paul Krugman for his research on business models and the location of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a New Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is also a famous New York Times editorialist.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration's economic and foreign policy solutions.
A few months after the attacks of September 2001, during the days of Enron's bankruptcy, Krugman wrote in an article published on the New York Times that the second event would have been more decisive than the first, in terms of consequences for the history of the United States.
A forecast that sparked many polemics, and which was criticized by the economist for years, but which has now proved to be accurate.
"I am surprised and even a little shocked at the speed with which the memory of scandals such as the collapse of Enron or Worldcom, disappeared from the attention of the public," said Krugman at the end of 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is a "high-value economist", but also a very aggressive divulgator, particularly critical of the excesses of liberalism in the Bush administration.
