Student victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student rental market is not in crisis
According to Sunia's latest survey, the tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin must support- explains the head of Sunia's study office, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand from students has so distorted the market that a process of general increase has even begun for residents.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: open-source contracts, unregistered contracts, rent limits, sub-rents.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the tax review are needed to calm prices.
Reading the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, it ranges from 650 euros minimum (Nere Bande zone), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), we ask about 600 euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (€550 for a simple one) for areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
We can save only if we move away in the peripheral areas: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a simple one in the area Predestina, Centocelle or similar.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, one spends 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed, it is necessary to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a simple one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rents are often taken by extra-community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, cities elect historic halls.
Historical cinemas close in favor of Multiplexes.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image presented by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalisation of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-salles, and the death of consumption of mono-salles in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and filled with memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of road and so much emotion" observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, a film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar and the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and which told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way of living cinema, may be lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: over the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the rooms of the main cities that have paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, the Romaine Emilia is in the lead with 82 single theatre cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms that the first person responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy over the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed in an irrational way," observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but we should still guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the failed deliberation of credit in favour of traders: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not comply with existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between €16 million and €18 million per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city which, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote the single cinemas of the historic centres and on the outskirts.
Among the planned standards, there are measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted area, and will have special rates for parking and in certain parking spaces.
"It's an initiative that I like," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna putting in place other measures.
It is obvious, however, that to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that for me, has always been important: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New cinema Paradiso" that I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so much shared emotions, I turn on the other side not to see the panels blackened by dust.
